CONSUMER (2025-05-08 14:50:00+00): Stuck
AGENT (2025-05-08 15:02:00+00): Hey there, Carin. Thanks for chatting. Stress isn’t always bad – it’s how the body responds to a challenge. But chronic stress can take a toll. By navigating tough times, you’ll protect your physical and mental health. Here are 3 tips:
1. Try “triage.” (They do it in the ER.) Prioritize tasks, and don’t try to do everything.
2. Change the scenery. For example, if you’re stressed inside, look out a window, or step outdoors for a minute. Pause, breathe, and collect your thoughts.
3. Talk it out. Share your perspective with a trusted friend, coworker, neighbor, or therapist.
We hope these tips help. And remember, getting enough sleep matters, too. So especially in high stress times, aim for those 7 to 8 hours so your body can recover. We’ve sent over your 30 points. Take care!

CONSUMER (2025-05-08 15:05:00+00): Thank you. 
AGENT (2025-05-08 15:15:00+00): You're welcome!
AGENT (2025-05-12 17:12:00+00): Hello Carin, we hope you are having a wonderful week. Thanks for chatting with us about boosting happiness last week. We wanted to check in and see if you would be interested in some in-app content named “Start your path to happiness” . Let us know if you are interested, or if we can provide any further support!
CONSUMER (2025-05-12 17:24:00+00): Yes I’m definitely interested. 
AGENT (2025-05-12 17:27:00+00): Hi Carin! We have added the journey "Start your path to happiness" to your feed. Once you complete your current journeys they will populate automatically. Let us know if you need further support, we are always happy to help. Enjoy your day!  

CONSUMER (2025-05-12 17:30:00+00): Thank you. 
AGENT (2025-05-12 17:32:00+00): No problem! Is there anything else we can assist you with?
AGENT (2025-05-14 19:08:00+00): Hello Carin. We just wanted to check in with you as to how we can continue supporting you with journaling. We have some journeys that may be helpful such as: Spring into journaling & 7 days of mindfulness. Please let us know if you are interested in these journeys and we can get them added for you.


CONSUMER (2025-05-14 20:12:00+00): Yes please add both. I also love getting single day tips. 
AGENT (2025-05-14 20:46:00+00): We would be happy to, Carin! We have gone and added that content for you. 
CONSUMER (2025-05-14 20:46:00+00): Thank you. 
AGENT (2025-05-14 20:46:00+00): of course!
AGENT (2025-05-15 13:19:00+00): Hi Carin. Thanks for chatting with us about high stress moments last week. If you have any specific questions and are in need of any tips, resources or Journey's that align with your health interests, please let us know. We'd be happy to help, have a great rest of your day!
CONSUMER (2025-05-19 14:04:00+00): Approach 
AGENT (2025-05-19 14:05:00+00): Hey, Carin. Good to hear from you! Ever wonder how to build better goals? One tip is to set “approach” goals. This means defining what you’ll do — rather than what you’ll avoid. For example, instead of saying “I won’t eat candy” an approach goal could be “I’ll try fruit when I crave sugar.” Approach goals are linked with more positive feelings, and can be easier to stick with. So, what WILL you work on soon? Let us know!

We’ve sent over your 100 points. Hope you have a great week! 

CONSUMER (2025-05-19 14:07:00+00): I’ll work on drinking more water and less sugary beverages. 
AGENT (2025-05-19 14:08:00+00): Thank you for sharing! Is there anything else we can support you with today? 
CONSUMER (2025-05-19 14:27:00+00): I appreciate the encouragement and love affirmations. 
AGENT (2025-05-19 14:31:00+00): No problem! Have a good day!


CONSUMER (2025-05-19 15:58:00+00): Next steps
AGENT (2025-05-19 16:23:00+00): Great Carin! What would be most helpful? We can…
1. Schedule a follow-up appointment. 
2. Share info about why it’s good to see your PCP after the ED
3. Provide ideas for cheaper, faster care (for non-emergencies)
4. Get you more info about a health condition. 
5. Connect you with a Nurse Well Guide to help decode your discharge instructions. 

CONSUMER (2025-05-19 16:25:00+00): I’d love more information about cardiogenic pulmonary edema. 
AGENT (2025-05-19 16:27:00+00): It would be our pleasure Carin and what type of information are looking to understand more when it comes to cardiogenic pulmonary edema?
CONSUMER (2025-05-19 16:39:00+00): Management and living a full life with it. 
AGENT (2025-05-19 16:56:00+00): Would you be interested in starting a SMART goal tailored around management?
CONSUMER (2025-05-19 16:57:00+00): Yes please. 
AGENT (2025-05-19 17:15:00+00): We see you’ve done SMART goals before, and look forward to working with you again. You can earn 50 points for setting a new goal with us today, and 100 points for weekly follow-ups.
AGENT (2025-05-19 17:15:00+00): We’ve adjusted this process recently, so that specific goals tie to a big picture “vision” of what you’d like to accomplish when it comes to health and wellness.
AGENT (2025-05-19 17:15:00+00): 
 So let’s start there today.
CONSUMER (2025-05-19 17:18:00+00): Goal: learn more about living with cardiogenic pulmonary edema. 
CONSUMER (2025-05-19 17:18:00+00): I can start by researching the internet and talking with my doctor. 
AGENT (2025-05-19 17:44:00+00): Thank you for sharing that with us Carin and we certainly want to support in learning more about that condition. If you like we can work with our internal team to see what information we can share around that for you. Is that something you would like for us to do and if so would you like to pause your SMART goal till you get some of the information to look over? 
CONSUMER (2025-05-19 17:50:00+00): That would be great. Thank you. 
AGENT (2025-05-19 18:07:00+00): It's our pleasure Carin. We will go ahead and reach out to our internal team to support you further in regard to learning more about living with Cardiogenic pulmonary edema.
AGENT (2025-05-19 18:07:00+00): And just to confirm, when would you like to come back and restart your Smart goal?
CONSUMER (2025-05-19 18:10:00+00): In 1 week. Thank you. 
AGENT (2025-05-19 18:12:00+00): No problem. We will reach back out to you in a week.
AGENT (2025-05-19 21:08:00+00): Hello Carin and happy Monday! We are reaching back out regarding your inquiry about information on cardiogenic pulmonary edema. We greatly appreciate your time and patience while we conducted our search. At this time, we would like to share a couple of resources from our sources, the National Institutes of Health (NIH) and Healthline.
AGENT (2025-05-19 21:08:00+00): According to the National Institutes of Health (NIH), pulmonary edema can be broadly classified into cardiogenic and noncardiogenic pulmonary edema. Cardiogenic involves the heart and noncardiogenic involves the lungs. Pulmonary edema can be a result of multiorgan involvement, and hence the involvement of an interprofessional team such as internists (primary care provider), cardiology (cardiologist), pulmonology (pulmonologist) early in the course is recommended for timely initiation of targeted therapy to improve patient outcomes.
AGENT (2025-05-19 21:08:00+00): Pulmonary Edema

https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK557611/
AGENT (2025-05-19 21:08:00+00): According to Healthline, The best way to try and prevent pulmonary edema is by taking good care of your health: get a pneumonia vaccine and the flu vaccine (especially if you have heart problems or are an older adult), remain on diuretics after an episode of pulmonary edema to prevent a re-occurrence.
AGENT (2025-05-19 21:08:00+00): You can also decrease your risk for heart failure, the most common cause of pulmonary edema with the following steps: visit a doctor regularly, avoid smoking or quit smoking if you smoke, avoid illegal drugs, get regular exercise, eat nutritious foods, and maintain your weight.


AGENT (2025-05-19 21:09:00+00): What Is Pulmonary Edema?
https://www.healthline.com/health/pulmonary-edema

AGENT (2025-05-19 21:09:00+00): Carin, please keep in mind that, while our information is gathered from evidence-based sources, we do not practice medicine and this information should not be used in place of your provider’s guidance. We encourage you to continue to stay connected with your provider to discuss this topic in more detail and to follow their guidelines. You can share this information with them to see what additional support they can offer. Remember that your provider can work with you to create a plan of care and/or make recommendations that are relevant to you and your health needs.
AGENT (2025-05-19 21:10:00+00): We hope these resources are beneficial to your health and wellness journey. Let us know if we can support further around this topic. We hope you have an amazing week!
CONSUMER (2025-05-19 21:12:00+00): This is great information. Thank you. 
AGENT (2025-05-19 21:31:00+00): Of course Carin, we are glad we are able to support you with the information, and we hope that your Monday evening is going well for you!
AGENT (2025-05-21 13:57:00+00): Hey Carin! We are here to help with setting a SMART goal. Would you still be interested in this SMART Goal or another topic of your choice! If any of these things would interest you, please feel free to chat in!


CONSUMER (2025-05-21 14:15:00+00): Yes I’d like to start a new goal. Something about forgiveness. 
AGENT (2025-05-21 14:19:00+00): We would be happy to support Carin. Let’s start with that big picture vision… When you think about the future, what do you want in terms of forgiveness? 
CONSUMER (2025-05-21 14:33:00+00): Forgiving doctors who made medical mistakes that negatively affected my life. It’s happened often unfortunately. 
AGENT (2025-05-21 14:58:00+00): THanks for sharing,Carin. How will you benefit if you start to forgive more?
CONSUMER (2025-05-21 15:29:00+00): I’m hoping to decrease anxiety at doctor’s appointments. 
AGENT (2025-05-21 16:24:00+00): Thank you foe letting us know. At Well, we use a “SMART” framework to set goals. You should use each letter as a guide to create a single goal. Think about what you’d like to change and how it could fit in this framework.

AGENT (2025-05-21 16:24:00+00): S = Specific. Focus on 1 clear change at a time.

AGENT (2025-05-21 16:24:00+00): M = Measurable. Consider how often or how long you want to work on it.

AGENT (2025-05-21 16:24:00+00): A = Action-oriented. Define something within your control. And focus on what you CAN do – not what you'll avoid.

AGENT (2025-05-21 16:24:00+00): R = Realistic. Goals should feel challenging, but doable. Consider what resources and support will make this goal reachable for you. 

AGENT (2025-05-21 16:24:00+00): T = Time-bound. Goals should include a timeline of when you’ll start, finish, or check on progress.

AGENT (2025-05-21 16:26:00+00): You said that you want to decrease anxiety at your doctor's appoints. What action will you do to achieve this goal?

CONSUMER (2025-05-21 16:28:00+00): Decrease thoughts about past mistakes 
AGENT (2025-05-21 16:54:00+00): Thank you so much, Carin. Looks like for your goal you are looking to decrease thoughts about past mistakes. Can you tell us a bit more around how you are looking to do that? Is there a specific activity or exercise you are looking to do when a thought surfaces?
CONSUMER (2025-05-21 16:56:00+00): Journaling has helped me. I can write about how I’m feeling and use affirmations to help decrease negative thoughts. 
AGENT (2025-05-21 17:25:00+00): We sincerely appreciate you sharing a bit more about this specific goal, Carin. Really amazing work so far! Are you looking to do this every time a thought surface, or dedicate some time on your day for journaling (if so, how long?)
CONSUMER (2025-05-21 17:29:00+00): Dedicated time for journaling prior to each doctor’s appointment. 
AGENT (2025-05-21 18:08:00+00): Great! And how will you measure whether or not you completed your goal? Additionally, how many times this week will you be journaling?
CONSUMER (2025-05-21 18:13:00+00): I have an appointment tomorrow so I’ll start tomorrow. I’d like to extend this goal for 3 months as I have several upcoming doctors appointments. 
AGENT (2025-05-21 18:45:00+00): That is a great goal to focus on Carin. As you look to get started what do you need to begin your goal? Also does this goal feel like this is enough of a challenge, but not too much?


CONSUMER (2025-05-21 19:43:00+00): I have everything I need and I think this goal is absolutely attainable. 
AGENT (2025-05-21 19:56:00+00): Excellent! Just a couple more questions to go. As you think about making this change, what type of support might need to have in place? (Like someone who can lend a hand, or an external support like a reminder system.)

CONSUMER (2025-05-21 20:00:00+00): I set a reminder on my phone. 
AGENT (2025-05-21 20:04:00+00): Now that we’ve set your goal, let’s make a plan to follow-up. We can coach you for up to 4 weeks on a goal. How many more sessions do you want?

CONSUMER (2025-05-21 20:36:00+00): 4 weeks please. 
AGENT (2025-05-21 20:44:00+00): In summary, you’ve defined your vision as decrease anxiety at doctor’s appointments. And a step you are taking this week towards achieving it is to write about how I’m feeling and use affirmations to help decrease negative thoughts.. 
AGENT (2025-05-21 20:45:00+00): Thanks so much for working on this with us today.  We have awarded you 50 points. We’ll reach out in 1 week to check-in on your goal.
CONSUMER (2025-05-21 20:45:00+00): Great. Thank you. 
AGENT (2025-05-21 20:47:00+00): Our pleasure!
AGENT (2025-05-27 19:27:00+00): Hi again, Carin! We wanted to let you know of a journey available to you called “Quiz Time! Have You Tried Telehealth?”. If interested, let us know, and we'll be more than happy to add this to your queue.
CONSUMER (2025-05-27 19:29:00+00): Yes that would be great. 
AGENT (2025-05-27 19:47:00+00): Great! We have gone ahead and added that journey for you. Please feel free to reach out anytime if we can ever assist you with anything else.
AGENT (2025-05-28 16:10:00+00): Hi, Carin. It’s time to check in on your SMART goal. How would you rate your progress this week? (Using a scale from 0%-100% where 0 = you didn’t work on it to 100% if you fully completed it.)
CONSUMER (2025-05-28 16:18:00+00): 95….I’m pretty determined once I set my mind to something. 
AGENT (2025-05-28 16:57:00+00): Awesome, Carin! Sounds like determination paid off!

AGENT (2025-05-28 16:57:00+00): What have you learned about yourself as you worked on this recently?
CONSUMER (2025-05-28 17:00:00+00): I’m a very strong willed individual. I suffer from PTSD due to doctors’ mistakes in the past that almost killed me. Little by little I’m working on regaining trust and lowering anxiety regarding doctors appointments. 
AGENT (2025-05-28 17:03:00+00): Thanks for sharing, Carin. Given your experience in the past week, let’s talk about what you may need to best support you going forward. What skills, social support, or resources would help you make progress?

CONSUMER (2025-05-28 17:04:00+00): I’m working with a therapist already and that’s helping immensely. I journal before appointments to calm myself. 
AGENT (2025-05-28 17:09:00+00): Perfect, Carin. Sounds like journaling & therapy worked for you.

CONSUMER (2025-05-28 17:10:00+00): Yes thank you. 
AGENT (2025-05-28 17:13:00+00): Perfect, Carin. For this coming week, would you like to stick with the same goal, or make any changes? 

CONSUMER (2025-05-28 17:13:00+00): Same goal please. 
AGENT (2025-05-28 17:20:00+00): Sounds good, Carin. You will continue working on the same goal.
Your goal will still be to dedicate time for journaling prior to each doctor’s appointment in order to avoid past mistakes
CONSUMER (2025-05-28 17:20:00+00): Sounds great. Thank you. 
AGENT (2025-05-28 17:22:00+00): Your welcome, Carin! 
How confident are you, from 0-10 that you can reach this goal? (Where 0 is not at all confident and 10 is extremely confident)

CONSUMER (2025-05-28 18:03:00+00): 9
AGENT (2025-05-28 18:38:00+00): Thanks for chatting today. As a reminder, your wellness vision is to decrease anxiety at doctor's appointments. And this week, you’ve set a goal to write about what you are feeling when you are experiencing negative feelings and use affirmations to help decrease negative thoughts. We have awarded your 100 points and will reach out to you next week. If you have a preferred day or time, please let us know.

CONSUMER (2025-05-28 18:38:00+00): Great. Thank you. 
AGENT (2025-05-28 18:45:00+00): It's our pleasure Carin.  Have a great rest of the week!

--Looking at age and response type
with pco_members as (select consumer_id, age from `hero_raw.chat_metrics`
left join (select consumer_id, age from `hero_derived.consumer_latest_metrics`) using (consumer_id)
where pco_name = 'C_HIGH_STRESS_MYHEALTH_TRACKING_TREND' and the_date between '2025-05-05' and '2025-06-05')

, responses as (select distinct consumer_id,sender_type, message_text, pcos_responded_to, client_name, datetime(the_timestamp, 'America/New_York') as the_timestamp, 1 as he_response from `hero_raw.chat_metrics`
where is_pco_response = 1 and the_date between '2025-05-05' and '2025-06-05' and pcos_responded_to = 'C_HIGH_STRESS_MYHEALTH_TRACKING_TREND'
order by consumer_id, the_timestamp)

, response_no_auto as (select consumer_id,sender_type, message_text, pcos_responded_to, client_name, the_date, datetime(the_timestamp, 'America/New_York') as the_timestamp from `hero_raw.chat_metrics`
where pco_name = 'C_HIGH_STRESS_MYHEALTH_TRACKING_TREND' and the_date between '2025-05-05' and '2025-06-05'
and consumer_id not in (select consumer_id from responses)
)
 
, health_engine_miss as (select consumer_id, the_timestamp_case_opened as the_timestamp, 0 as he_response from response_no_auto
left join (select consumer_id, case_number, subject, datetime(the_timestamp_case_opened, 'America/New_York') as the_timestamp_case_opened, datetime(timestamp_add(the_timestamp_case_opened, interval cast(minutes_to_close as int64) minute), 'America/New_York') as the_timestamp_case_closed from `hero_raw.salesforce_cases_metrics` where most_recent_update = 1 and case_type = 'parent_case' and regexp_contains(lower(subject), 'high stress moment pco')) using (consumer_id)
where (date(timestamp(the_timestamp_case_opened, 'America/New_York')) < '2025-06-05' and date(timestamp(the_timestamp_case_opened, 'America/New_York')) >= '2025-05-05')
and date_diff(the_timestamp_case_opened, the_timestamp, minute) >= 0 
)

, joined as (select coalesce(a.consumer_id,b.consumer_id,c.consumer_id) as consumer_id,  age,  min(coalesce(b.the_timestamp,c.the_timestamp)) over (partition by coalesce(a.consumer_id,b.consumer_id,c.consumer_id)) as first_timestamp, coalesce(b.he_response, c.he_response) as he_flag  from pco_members a
full outer join responses b using (consumer_id)
full outer join health_engine_miss c using (consumer_id)
)

, message_clarity as (select consumer_id, age, b.message_text, b.sender_type, b.the_timestamp, first_timestamp, row_number() over (partition by b.the_timestamp order by b.the_timestamp desc) as row_num, he_flag from joined 
left join `hero_raw.chat_metrics` b using (consumer_id)
where datetime(b.the_timestamp) >= first_timestamp and (date(b.the_timestamp) < date('2024-11-08') and date(b.the_timestamp) > date('2024-03-01'))
and b.sender_type != 'AUTO')

, agged AS (
SELECT age, consumer_id,
substr(array_to_string(array_agg(concat(sender_type, ' (', cast(timestamp_trunc(timestamp(the_timestamp), MINUTE) as string), '): ', message_text) order by the_timestamp), '\n'), 1, 25000) agg_message_text, first_timestamp, he_flag
FROM message_clarity
where row_num = 1
group by 2,1, 4,5
order by 4 asc
)

--/*
select * from agged
order by first_timestamp asc
--*/


--select consumer_id, count(*) from responses
--group by 1 order by 2 desc

AGENT (2025-05-08 16:26:00+00): Hey there, Alec. Thanks for chatting. Stress isn’t always bad – it’s how the body responds to a challenge. But chronic stress can take a toll. By navigating tough times, you’ll protect your physical and mental health. Here are 3 tips:
1. Try “triage.” (They do it in the ER.) Prioritize tasks, and don’t try to do everything.
2. Change the scenery. For example, if you’re stressed inside, look out a window, or step outdoors for a minute. Pause, breathe, and collect your thoughts.
3. Talk it out. Share your perspective with a trusted friend, coworker, neighbor, or therapist.
We hope these tips help. And remember, getting enough sleep matters, too. So especially in high stress times, aim for those 7 to 8 hours so your body can recover. We’ve sent over your 30 points. Take care!

AGENT (2025-05-15 21:34:00+00): Hi, we hope your day is going well, Alec. Let us know if you’d like any stress management tips, or other support for stress. We’re standing by.

AGENT (2025-05-14 17:15:00+00): Hey, Erick. Good to hear from you! Ever wonder how to build better goals? One tip is to set “approach” goals. This means defining what you’ll do — rather than what you’ll avoid. For example, instead of saying “I won’t eat candy” an approach goal could be “I’ll try fruit when I crave sugar.” Approach goals are linked with more positive feelings, and can be easier to stick with. So, what WILL you work on soon? Let us know!

We’ve sent over your 100 points. Hope you have a great week!
CONSUMER (2025-05-19 15:32:00+00): Organize my meds
AGENT (2025-05-19 16:00:00+00): Hi, Erick. We’re here with tips for organizing meds. Here are four different ways to keep track of your pills.

Get a pill box. These are special boxes with compartments for each of your meds. They come in all shapes and sizes. You can choose one with as many compartments as you need. And you can fill up your pill box on a daily, weekly or monthly basis. You can get these at the pharmacy or online.
Try an automatic pill dispenser. These are electronic devices that you (or a trusted friend or doctor) can program to automatically dispense your dose when you need it. They often have light or other signal to notify you when to take your meds, so you don’t miss a dose.
Use a color-coded system. This is helpful if you have meds for different times of day. Get a pack of colored labels to stick on your prescriptions. For example, assign green to your morning meds, blue to lunch-time meds and purple to nighttime meds. Then, you won't mix up when to take each pill.
Create a med checklist. Make a chart that lists each med, the dose, and what time you’ll take it. Then, check it off immediately after you take it. That way, you can refer back to the list if you’re not sure which meds you’ve taken yet. 

We hope this helps you stay on top of your meds. And we’ve sent 30 points!

AGENT (2025-05-27 17:04:00+00): Hey Erick, thanks again for chatting with us about organizing your medications. Have you tried any of the tips yet? Let us know if we can provide any more support around this topic!


CONSUMER (2025-06-04 16:40:00+00): Spring cleaning
AGENT (2025-06-04 16:41:00+00): Good Afternoon, Erick. Do you have a space in mind that you’re ready to organize? If not, pick one out, since today is all about decluttering. Here are 3 tips to get going:

AGENT (2025-06-04 16:41:00+00): Step 1: Make 3 sorting piles (or bins). Label these as “Need it,” “Maybe,” or “Don’t need.” Take your time going through items. Challenge yourself to consider what things you could donate, recycle, or give away. 

AGENT (2025-06-04 16:41:00+00): Step 2: After sorting all piles, aim to move half (or more) of the “Maybe” pile into the “Don’t need” pile. Then, make a plan of where (and when) you can give or get rid of these items.

AGENT (2025-06-04 16:41:00+00): Step 3: Clean up time! Reorganize with labels, boxes, etc. Enlist the support of someone you trust to make the job easier. 

AGENT (2025-06-04 16:41:00+00): We have sent over your 30 points and hope you have a wonderful rest of your day!

AGENT (2025-06-03 21:27:00+00): Hello, Michael! Thanks for chatting with us about microplastics. Here are 6 quick tips to limit your exposure to these tiny plastic particles. 

Skip the plastic containers and water bottles. Instead, try reusable containers made of aluminum or glass. 
Swap out any personal care products that contain microbeads. Instead choose face washes and toothpastes that are labeled “plastic-free.” 
Avoid putting plastic under high heat. That means hand-washing plastics instead of using the dishwasher, and not microwaving plastics. 
Use wood or bamboo cutting boards instead of plastic. That way, you’ll avoid plastic pieces breaking off into the food you’re cutting,
Drink filtered water. You can install a filter on your sink to keep microplastics out of your tap water. 
Clean your air. A HEPA air filter will trap plastic particles and keep the air in your home plastic-free. 

Enjoy your 30 points!

Try an automatic pill dispenser. These are electronic devices that you (or a trusted friend or doctor) can program to automatically dispense your dose when you need it. They often have light or other signal to notify you when to take your meds, so you don’t miss a dose.

AGENT (2025-05-08 20:57:00+00): Hey, Wendy! Thanks for chatting. You’re not alone if you get heartburn from GLP-1 meds. Here are some simple tips that might help:

Try smaller portion sizes.
Avoid eating too close to bedtime.
Sleep on your left side, with the head of your bed elevated.
If you notice any foods make your heartburn worse, try avoiding them. Things like spicy food, citrus fruits, coffee, and chocolate are common culprits.
Remember that most side effects from GLP-1 meds get better with time.
Talk to your provider for more ideas, or to see if meds might help.

We hope these tips are helpful! Enjoy the rest of your day and the 30 points!

CONSUMER (2025-05-10 22:38:00+00): SMART MOOD
AGENT (2025-05-12 10:42:00+00): Hi Wendy! 
You can earn 50 points for setting a new goal with us today, and 100 points for weekly follow-ups.
We’ve adjusted this process recently, so that specific goals tie to a big picture “vision” of what you’d like to accomplish when it comes to health and wellness. So let’s start there today.

In a sentence (or two) can you please share what you’d like to achieve in the long-run with your health or wellness? We call this a “wellness vision.
CONSUMER (2025-05-12 11:10:00+00): The vision I have toward my future good health begins with every healthful food choice I make today. What has helped me the most so far is beginning my day with reflection and mindfulness meditation with my walk with the Lord and then a kale, blueberry and protein smoothie.
I have found that this begins my day with a solid foundation and energy to step into the new day with courage and determination. 
Secondly, I give myself room for imperfection and chalk up my mistakes as a learning experience and move on.
My new manta is “Eat the rainbow 🌈!”

Try smaller portion sizes.
Avoid eating too close to bedtime.
Sleep on your left side, with the head of your bed elevated.
If you notice any foods make your heartburn worse, try avoiding them. Things like spicy food, citrus fruits, coffee, and chocolate are common culprits.
Remember that most side effects from GLP-1 meds get better with time.
Talk to your provider for more ideas, or to see if meds might help.

We hope these tips are helpful! Enjoy the rest of your day and the 30 points!

AGENT (2025-05-08 23:31:00+00): Hello, Ronda! Thanks for chatting. Stress isn’t always bad – it’s how the body responds to a challenge. But chronic stress can take a toll. By navigating tough times, you’ll protect your physical and mental health. Here are 3 tips:
AGENT (2025-05-08 23:31:00+00):  1. Try “triage.” (They do it in the ER.) Prioritize tasks, and don’t try to do everything. 2. Change the scenery. For example, if you’re stressed inside, look out a window, or step outdoors for a minute. Pause, breathe, and collect your thoughts. 3. Talk it out. Share your perspective with a trusted friend, coworker, neighbor, or therapist. We hope these tips help. And remember, getting enough sleep matters, too. So especially in high stress times, aim for those 7 to 8 hours so your body can recover.

1. Try “triage.” (They do it in the ER.) Prioritize tasks, and don’t try to do everything.
2. Change the scenery. For example, if you’re stressed inside, look out a window, or step outdoors for a minute. Pause, breathe, and collect your thoughts.
3. Talk it out. Share your perspective with a trusted friend, coworker, neighbor, or therapist.

We hope these tips help. And remember, getting enough sleep matters, too. So especially in high stress times, aim for those 7 to 8 hours so your body can recover. We’ve sent over your 30 points. Take care!

AGENT (2025-05-12 14:34:00+00): Hello, Michelle! Thanks for chatting. Stress isn’t always bad – it’s how the body responds to a challenge. But chronic stress can take a toll. By navigating tough times, you’ll protect your physical and mental health.
AGENT (2025-05-12 14:34:00+00): Here are 3 tips: 1. Try “triage.” (They do it in the ER.) Prioritize tasks, and don’t try to do everything. 2. Change the scenery. For example, if you’re stressed inside, look out a window, or step outdoors for a minute. Pause, breathe, and collect your thoughts. 3. Talk it out. Share your perspective with a trusted friend, coworker, neighbor, or therapist. We hope these tips help. And remember, getting enough sleep matters, too.
AGENT (2025-05-12 14:34:00+00): So especially in high stress times, aim for those 7 to 8 hours so your body can recover. We’ve sent over your 30 points. Take care!

We will have some options available for you soon, we just need to verify the providers that we found and we can send them over. If you would also like for us to set up an appointment when we call, let us know and we will collect information from you to do so. Have a great day and talk to you soon!

CONSUMER (2025-05-20 17:15:00+00): Heartburn
AGENT (2025-05-20 17:26:00+00): Hello, Michelle! Thanks for chatting. You’re not alone if you get heartburn from GLP-1 meds. Here are some simple tips that might help:

Try smaller portion sizes.
Avoid eating too close to bedtime.
Sleep on your left side, with the head of your bed elevated.
If you notice any foods make your heartburn worse, try avoiding them. Things like spicy food, citrus fruits, coffee, and chocolate are common culprits.
Remember that most side effects from GLP-1 meds get better with time.
Talk to your provider for more ideas, or to see if meds might help.

We hope these tips are helpful! Enjoy the rest of your day and the 30 points!
AGENT (2025-05-27 17:42:00+00): Hi Michelle, hope all is well! Thanks for reaching out recently about getting connected to a provider for ADHD.  We wanted to share an article from our trusted partner Healthwise about how to make the most of your appointment.  Please let us know what you think or if we can be of any further support.  Have a great day!

https://www.healthwise.net/well/Content/StdDocument.aspx?DOCHWID=hw226888
CONSUMER (2025-05-28 22:12:00+00): Protein power
AGENT (2025-05-28 22:13:00+00): Hello, Michelle! Protein helps keep your muscles strong, and it can prevent overeating too. But not all protein is created equal. Here are some ideas to eat healthy, lean proteins at every meal:
AGENT (2025-05-28 22:13:00+00): 1) Breakfast: Try Greek yogurt, eggs, or chia pudding.
2) Lunch: Dine on lentil soup, chickpea salad, or turkey roll-ups.
3) Snack: Try veggies and hummus or apples and peanut butter.
4) Dinner: Eat poultry, seafood, or black bean tacos.
CONSUMER (2025-06-02 14:51:00+00): Affirmation
AGENT (2025-06-02 14:59:00+00): Hello, Michelle! Many people find it hard to start or stick with a goal when they doubt themselves, or their ability. If this comes up for you, a simple way to bolster confidence is through affirmations. These are simple statements that recognize your personal strengths or effort. Like telling yourself, “I’m strong” or “My sense of humor will get me through.” 

If you’re not sure what your strengths are, think about a past hardship that you overcame. What helped you? (Look for strengths like dedication, hard work, creativity, or teamwork).

We’ve sent over your 100 points. Have a great day!
AGENT (2025-06-03 17:36:00+00): Hello Michelle, we hope you are having a wonderful week. Thanks for chatting with us about protein last week. We wanted to check in and see if you would be interested in some in-app content named “Be a label lover” . Let us know if you are interested, or if we can provide any further support!

column4:
CONSUMER (2025-05-12 17:15:00+00): stuck
AGENT (2025-05-12 17:19:00+00): Hello, Debora! Thanks for chatting. Stress isn’t always bad – it’s how the body responds to a challenge. But chronic stress can take a toll. By navigating tough times, you’ll protect your physical and mental health. Here are 3 tips:
1. Try “triage.” (They do it in the ER.) Prioritize tasks, and don’t try to do everything.
2. Change the scenery. For example, if you’re stressed inside, look out a window, or step outdoors for a minute. Pause, breathe, and collect your thoughts.
3. Talk it out. Share your perspective with a trusted friend, coworker, neighbor, or therapist.
We hope these tips help. And remember, getting enough sleep matters, too. So especially in high stress times, aim for those 7 to 8 hours so your body can recover. We’ve sent over your 30 points. Take care!
CONSUMER (2025-05-23 19:07:00+00): Approach
AGENT (2025-05-23 19:08:00+00): Hey, Debora. Good to hear from you! Ever wonder how to build better goals? One tip is to set “approach” goals. This means defining what you’ll do — rather than what you’ll avoid. For example, instead of saying “I won’t eat candy” an approach goal could be “I’ll try fruit when I crave sugar.” Approach goals are linked with more positive feelings, and can be easier to stick with. So, what WILL you work on soon? Let us know!


AGENT (2025-05-23 19:08:00+00): 
We’ve sent over your 100 points. Hope you have a great week! 
CONSUMER (2025-05-27 14:27:00+00): 30 grams?
AGENT (2025-05-27 14:31:00+00): Sugar shock! A can of soda packs a whopping 10 teaspoons of added sugar. That’s a lot — considering we should limit to about 12 teaspoons each day. But not to worry! Here are some delicious swaps that won’t leave you feeling sticky: 



AGENT (2025-05-27 14:32:00+00): Sparkling water (with a dash of juice).
Ice cold water with a slice of cucumber, lemon, or mint.
A no-sugar-added smoothie, sweetened with dates and bananas.
Coconut water with a squeeze of lime juice.
Sugar-free sweeteners (for coffee, tea, or soda).


AGENT (2025-05-27 14:33:00+00): Remember to check the nutrition label for “added sugars” before you grab your next drink. Enjoy your 30 points.
AGENT (2025-06-03 13:53:00+00): Hello, Debora. Thanks for chatting with us last week about sugary drinks. Did you have a chance to try out one of the swaps? Check out this resource for more ideas: 
https://www.myplate.gov/tip-sheet/cut-back-added-sugars
CONSUMER (2025-06-04 17:08:00+00): microplastics
AGENT (2025-06-04 17:09:00+00): Hello, Debora! Thanks for chatting with us about microplastics. Here are 6 quick tips to limit your exposure to these tiny plastic particles. 

Skip the plastic containers and water bottles. Instead, try reusable containers made of aluminum or glass. 
Swap out any personal care products that contain microbeads. Instead choose face washes and toothpastes that are labeled “plastic-free.” 
Avoid putting plastic under high heat. That means hand-washing plastics instead of using the dishwasher, and not microwaving plastics. 
Use wood or bamboo cutting boards instead of plastic. That way, you’ll avoid plastic pieces breaking off into the food you’re cutting,
Drink filtered water. You can install a filter on your sink to keep microplastics out of your tap water. 
Clean your air. A HEPA air filter will trap plastic particles and keep the air in your home plastic-free. 

Enjoy your 30 points!

CONSUMER (2025-05-28 19:20:00+00): Toothbrush tips
AGENT (2025-05-28 19:23:00+00): Hello, Lyn! Here are some tips to keep your toothbrush fresh (and your teeth strong):.


AGENT (2025-05-28 19:23:00+00): Check the bristles on your toothbrush. When they’re bent or frayed, it’s time for a replacement.
Mark your calendar, or set a reminder on your phone to notify you 3 months after you start a new toothbrush. 
Consider changing your toothbrush at the beginning of each season. This will keep you on a 3 to 4 month timeline.
Keep a pack of spare toothbrushes (or electric brush-heads) in your bathroom. Having extras will make it easier to replace your brush at the 3 to 4 month mark.

CONSUMER (2025-05-21 14:17:00+00): water safety
AGENT (2025-05-21 14:19:00+00): Hello, Theresa! Thanks for chatting about water safety. Here are some tips to help keep you and your family safe: 

AGENT (2025-05-21 14:19:00+00): 1. Supervise children closely around water. And dress them in bright bathing suits, so they’ll stand out from the water.

2. Install a fence around all sides of home pools. It should be over 4 feet tall and have a lock that is out of children’s reach.

3. Enroll kids in swimming lessons, where they can learn water survival skills. 

4. Always have life jackets for all ages. You can’t rely on blow-up objects like rafts and pool toys as life preservers. 

5. Always swim with others. It’s especially safe when there’s a lifeguard present. 

6. Avoid mixing alcohol with water activities. 

Thanks again for chatting in today. We hope you have a fun and safe time in the water!
AGENT (2025-05-28 20:34:00+00): Hello Theresa! We hope you gained some water wisdom last week. Here’s a link with more tips to prevent drowning: https://www.cdc.gov/drowning/prevention/index.html 
CONSUMER (2025-05-30 13:04:00+00): spring cleaning
AGENT (2025-05-30 13:12:00+00): Hello, Theresa! Do you have a space in mind that you’re ready to organize? If not, pick one out, since today is all about decluttering. Here are 3 tips to get going:

Step 1: Make 3 sorting piles (or bins). Label these as “Need it,” “Maybe,” or “Don’t need.” Take your time going through items. Challenge yourself to consider what things you could donate, recycle, or give away. 

Step 2: After sorting all piles, aim to move half (or more) of the “Maybe” pile into the “Don’t need” pile. Then, make a plan of where (and when) you can give or get rid of these items.


Step 3: Clean up time! Reorganize with labels, boxes, etc. Enlist the support of someone you trust to make the job easier. 

We have sent over your 30 points and hope you have a wonderful rest of your day!

AGENT (2025-05-13 14:37:00+00): Hello, Joey! Good to hear from you! Ever wonder how to build better goals? One tip is to set “approach” goals. This means defining what you’ll do — rather than what you’ll avoid. For example, instead of saying “I won’t eat candy” an approach goal could be “I’ll try fruit when I crave sugar.” Approach goals are linked with more positive feelings, and can be easier to stick with. So, what WILL you work on soon? Let us know!

We’ve sent over your 100 points. Hope you have a great week!

AGENT (2025-05-23 19:23:00+00): When stress comes from taking on too much, it is important to sometimes be able to say “no” and also think about what you can let go of to make your life a bit easier. Start by reviewing your list of priorities and daily responsibilities. Think about any areas where you may have taken on too much. Ask yourself if there are any responsibilities you can let go of – now or in the future.


AGENT (2025-05-23 19:23:00+00): If you have trouble saying “no” when others ask you to do things, consider practicing assertiveness. Assertiveness is an appropriate way to express your thoughts, feelings, needs and desires. Acting in an assertive way helps you to stand up for yourself, without being too passive or aggressive which can come across the wrong way. 


AGENT (2025-05-23 19:23:00+00): Here are a few tips to help with practicing assertiveness:

Try to keep your body posture relaxed and open. Make direct eye contact if you can. Keep a level tone of voice.

Use I- Statements to express how you feel, what you think or want. For example: “I’ve got a lot on my plate right now, so I’m sorry I won’t be able to take that on this week. Maybe another time.”

Try the Broken Record strategy of simply repeating your “no” answer.

2. Change the scenery. For example, if you’re stressed inside, look out a window, or step outdoors for a minute. Pause, breathe, and collect your thoughts.
3. Talk it out. Share your perspective with a trusted friend, coworker, neighbor, or therapist.

So especially in high stress times, aim for those 7 to 8 hours so your body can recover. We’ve sent over your 30 points. Take care!

1. Try “triage.” (They do it in the ER.) Prioritize tasks, and don’t try to do everything.
2. Change the scenery. For example, if you’re stressed inside, look out a window, or step outdoors for a minute. Pause, breathe, and collect your thoughts.
3. Talk it out. Share your perspective with a trusted friend, coworker, neighbor, or therapist.
We hope these tips help. And remember, getting enough sleep matters, too. So especially in high stress times, aim for those 7 to 8 hours so your body can recover. We’ve sent over your 30 points. Take care!
AGENT (2025-05-13 19:09:00+00): Also ever wonder how to build better goals? One tip is to set “approach” goals. This means defining what you’ll do — rather than what you’ll avoid. For example, instead of saying “I won’t eat candy” an approach goal could be “I’ll try fruit when I crave sugar.” Approach goals are linked with more positive feelings, and can be easier to stick with. So, what WILL you work on soon? Let us know!

We’ve sent over your 100 points. Hope you have a great week!

AGENT (2025-05-21 12:11:00+00): Managing time and priorities under stress                          

Here are a few tips to work on managing your time better:
AGENT (2025-05-21 12:12:00+00): Write down how you spend a typical day.  Then, write down how an ideal day would go.  See if there is anything you can do to make your typical day just a little bit more like your ideal day. Start with 1 small thing.
Get better at setting priorities, and following through. Here are some steps:
AGENT (2025-05-21 12:12:00+00): Make a list of everything you are trying to do. Include household chores, and any work or caregiving responsibilities. 
Rank these in terms of what is most important. 
AGENT (2025-05-21 12:12:00+00): Think about what you can realistically do today, and what needs to be postponed. Look carefully at your list. Consider if there is anything that you could ask for help with… For example, can someone else clean or do the laundry? Is it worth paying someone to do some of the chores to refocus on other important things?
Finally, ask yourself- is there any ‘Me Time’ on this list? And if not, try to make 5-10 minutes for yourself to have a quick break. Use the break time to take a few deep breaths, or to step outside.

CONSUMER (2025-05-28 18:47:00+00): Side effects
AGENT (2025-05-28 19:23:00+00): Good Afternoon, Nicole. Thanks for chatting with us about side effects concerns. It’s normal to have these worries. But there are ways to manage it. Here are a few ways to cope if concerns about side effects are getting in the way of taking your medication. 

AGENT (2025-05-28 19:23:00+00): Try writing down your concerns. What side effects are you most concerned about? Then write down the benefits of taking the med. How could it improve your health and wellbeing? 
AGENT (2025-05-28 19:23:00+00): Share your concerns with your doctor. They can inform you about any possible side effects and how to manage them. And if you do experience side effects, let your doctor know, in case they want to adjust your med.
AGENT (2025-05-28 19:23:00+00): If you’re worried about safety, remember that meds are approved by the FDA. That means they’ve gone through many tests and studies to make sure they are safe and effective. The FDA wouldn’t approve something if side effects were more than mild or dangerous to your health.
AGENT (2025-05-28 19:24:00+00): Think big picture. Reflect on why you’re taking a med in the first place — to improve your health. Thinking about the pros of your med can help put worries about side effects in perspective. 
AGENT (2025-05-28 19:24:00+00): Enjoy your 30 points!
CONSUMER (2025-05-29 12:15:00+00): Thank you! 
AGENT (2025-05-29 12:48:00+00): No problem!
AGENT (2025-06-02 18:42:00+00): Hey, Nicole. Thanks for chatting with us last week about working through med side effect concerns. Did you try any of the coping tips we shared? Let us know how it went — and if you’d like any more information on this topic.
CONSUMER (2025-06-02 19:26:00+00): That was helpful thank you. If you could send over more stress management tips I would appreciate it 
AGENT (2025-06-02 19:27:00+00): Sure Nicole. Here are some basic stress management tips we can share with you. Please feel free to chat back and let us know if you would like more or if you would like to work on creating a goal to focus on a topic to help with stress and earn points in the process!

- Basic stress management tips
- Here is some basic information on managing stress:
- Know your personal signs of stress overload. (Like trouble falling asleep, feeling irritability, appetite changes, etc.).
- Get regular exercise, as long as your doctor approves, such as 30 minutes a day.
- Make time to connect with others.
- Make time for self-care and relaxation, daily if possible.
- Set goals and priorities.
- Ask for help when you need it.
- Work on managing time effectively.
- Keep your self-talk encouraging, rather than negative.
- Talk to a doctor or therapist if stress overwhelms.

Review this resources for more info and chat with us again soon: https://orwh.od.nih.gov/in-the-spotlight/all-articles/7-steps-manage-stress-and-build-resilience

CONSUMER (2025-05-23 03:04:00+00): Joyride
AGENT (2025-05-23 11:34:00+00): Hello, Kelly! When you’re feeling nauseous, go for bland foods. Here are some ideas:

Keep it simple with plain crackers, toast, or white rice.
Reach for apples or bananas.
Try ginger candy, or brew up some ginger tea.
Grab a sweet treat with Jell-O or popsicles.
Avoid foods that are fried, high in fat, super sweet, or spicy. These can make nausea worse.

Nausea from GLP-1 meds usually gets better with time. If it doesn’t, reach out to your provider. Enjoy the rest of your day and the 100 points!

CONSUMER (2025-06-03 03:02:00+00): Food journal
AGENT (2025-06-03 11:45:00+00): Good Morning, Kelly. Keeping a food diary can make you aware of what you’re eating and drinking… and how you feel after. Here are some tips to get started:


AGENT (2025-06-03 11:45:00+00): Choose your logging method — pen and paper or a digital device.
Establish a schedule: Track at each meal or at the end of the day. 
Include key details, like time of day, food/drink, portion sizes, and how you feel. 
Take some time to review it (on your own or with a provider). What patterns do you see? What’s working and what’s not? How might you adjust?


AGENT (2025-06-03 11:45:00+00): Check out this food diary template. It can be edited, printed, or used as a guide to create your own. Be sure to include how you feel after each time you eat or drink. Let us know if you have any questions and enjoy the 30 points!

3. Talk it out. Share your perspective with a trusted friend, coworker, neighbor, or therapist.

CONSUMER (2025-05-31 00:55:00+00): I’m chatting in. “Facts on fats”
AGENT (2025-05-31 00:57:00+00): Hello, Randi! You can get a few different types of fat from your diet — saturated, trans, and unsaturated fats. And these fats affect your cholesterol differently. 

Saturated and trans fats raise your LDL or “bad” cholesterol — which increases your risk of heart attack and stroke. Meanwhile, choosing unsaturated fats helps lower your cholesterol and promote heart health. So, when choosing foods to eat, do your best to…

- Limit saturated and trans fats: Saturated fats are common in dairy products like butter and cream cheese and fatty cuts of meats like beef and pork. Trans fats are in fried foods and baked goods like pastries and pizza. These are best in moderation.
- Choose unsaturated fats instead: Fish (like salmon and trout), avocados, nuts, lean meats, and unsaturated oils (like olive, canola, and safflower oils) are all examples of unsaturated fats. These healthy fats can help you reach your cholesterol goals. 

Choosing healthy fats is just one of many strategies to help lower your cholesterol — in addition to getting plenty of exercise, managing stress, and taking meds if your doctor recommends it. Enjoy your 100 points!

If you’re not sure what your strengths are, think about a past hardship that you overcame. What helped you? (Look for strengths like dedication, hard work, creativity, or teamwork).

We’ve sent over your 100 points. Have a great day!

AGENT (2025-05-27 16:18:00+00): Hello, Alissa! Thanks for chatting with us about side effects concerns. It’s normal to have these worries. But there are ways to manage it. Here are a few ways to cope if concerns about side effects are getting in the way of taking your medication. 


AGENT (2025-05-27 16:19:00+00): Try writing down your concerns. What side effects are you most concerned about? Then write down the benefits of taking the med. How could it improve your health and wellbeing? 

AGENT (2025-05-27 16:20:00+00): Share your concerns with your doctor. They can inform you about any possible side effects and how to manage them. And if you do experience side effects, let your doctor know, in case they want to adjust your med.

AGENT (2025-05-27 16:20:00+00): If you’re worried about safety, remember that meds are approved by the FDA. That means they’ve gone through many tests and studies to make sure they are safe and effective. The FDA wouldn’t approve something if side effects were more than mild or dangerous to your health.

AGENT (2025-05-27 16:20:00+00): Think big picture. Reflect on why you’re taking a med in the first place — to improve your health. Thinking about the pros of your med can help put worries about side effects in perspective. 

AGENT (2025-05-27 16:20:00+00): Enjoy your 30 points!
AGENT (2025-06-03 15:20:00+00): Hello, Alissa. Thanks for chatting with us last week about working through med side effect concerns. Did you try any of the coping tips we shared? Let us know how it went — and if you’d like any more information on this topic.
CONSUMER (2025-06-04 15:20:00+00): Organize 
AGENT (2025-06-04 15:28:00+00): Good Morning, Alissa. We’re here with tips for organizing meds. Here are four different ways to keep track of your pills.

AGENT (2025-06-04 15:28:00+00): Get a pill box. These are special boxes with compartments for each of your meds. They come in all shapes and sizes. You can choose one with as many compartments as you need. And you can fill up your pill box on a daily, weekly or monthly basis. You can get these at the pharmacy or online.

AGENT (2025-06-04 15:28:00+00): Try an automatic pill dispenser. These are electronic devices that you (or a trusted friend or doctor) can program to automatically dispense your dose when you need it. They often have light or other signal to notify you when to take your meds, so you don’t miss a dose.

AGENT (2025-06-04 15:28:00+00): Use a color-coded system. This is helpful if you have meds for different times of day. Get a pack of colored labels to stick on your prescriptions. For example, assign green to your morning meds, blue to lunch-time meds and purple to nighttime meds. Then, you won't mix up when to take each pill.

AGENT (2025-06-04 15:28:00+00): Create a med checklist. Make a chart that lists each med, the dose, and what time you’ll take it. Then, check it off immediately after you take it. That way, you can refer back to the list if you’re not sure which meds you’ve taken yet. 

AGENT (2025-06-04 15:28:00+00): We hope this helps you stay on top of your meds. And we’ve sent 30 points!

AGENT (2025-06-03 22:25:00+00): Hello, Hollie! Thanks for chatting. Stress isn’t always bad – it’s how the body responds to a challenge. But chronic stress can take a toll. By navigating tough times, you’ll protect your physical and mental health. Here are 3 tips:
1. Try “triage.” (They do it in the ER.) Prioritize tasks, and don’t try to do everything.
2. Change the scenery. For example, if you’re stressed inside, look out a window, or step outdoors for a minute. Pause, breathe, and collect your thoughts.
3. Talk it out. Share your perspective with a trusted friend, coworker, neighbor, or therapist.
We hope these tips help. And remember, getting enough sleep matters, too. So especially in high stress times, aim for those 7 to 8 hours so your body can recover. We’ve sent over your 30 points. Take care!

Here are some tips on strength training- are you interested in further tips or  setting a goal around walking as well?


 Strengthening your muscles can improve your fitness and even make your bones stronger. Here are some tips to get the most out of it:
Aim for at least 2 days per week.
Work all the major muscle groups, including the legs, hip, back, chest, abdomen, shoulders, and arms.
Think outside the box. Sure, weightlifting works. But so do bodyweight exercises, gardening, and resistance bands.
Focus on keeping good form first and foremost.
As you get stronger, you can slowly increase the intensity by doing more reps or adding more weight.
Take time to recover between strength training sessions.
As always, check with your doctor before starting or changing your exercise routine.

Enjoy your 30 points. Here’s to being stronger than yesterday!

AGENT (2025-05-30 17:43:00+00): You can get a few different types of fat from your diet — saturated, trans, and unsaturated fats. And these fats affect your cholesterol differently. 

AGENT (2025-05-30 17:43:00+00): Saturated and trans fats raise your LDL or “bad” cholesterol — which increases your risk of heart attack and stroke. Meanwhile, choosing unsaturated fats helps lower your cholesterol and promote heart health. So, when choosing foods to eat, do your best to…

AGENT (2025-05-30 17:44:00+00): - Limit saturated and trans fats: Saturated fats are common in dairy products like butter and cream cheese and fatty cuts of meats like beef and pork. Trans fats are in fried foods and baked goods like pastries and pizza. These are best in moderation.
- Choose unsaturated fats instead: Fish (like salmon and trout), avocados, nuts, lean meats, and unsaturated oils (like olive, canola, and safflower oils) are all examples of unsaturated fats. These healthy fats can help you reach your cholesterol goals. 

AGENT (2025-05-30 17:44:00+00): Choosing healthy fats is just one of many strategies to help lower your cholesterol — in addition to getting plenty of exercise, managing stress, and taking meds if your doctor recommends it. Enjoy your 100 points! If you have questions. Please chat back in.

CONSUMER (2025-05-28 23:28:00+00): Simplify my meds
AGENT (2025-05-28 23:33:00+00): Hello, Lynn! Thanks for chatting with us about taking multiple medications. Here are some quick tips to simplify your medication routine.


AGENT (2025-05-28 23:33:00+00): 1. Group your medications together. Instead of taking them at different times throughout the day, take them at the same time each day.
2. If you take a med multiple times a day, ask your doctor if you can switch to a once-daily version of the med, instead. 
3. Some meds can be combined together. Ask your doctor if a combination pill of two or more meds you take is available for you. That way, you’ll have fewer pills to take.

AGENT (2025-06-03 20:38:00+00): Hey, Florence!! Thanks for chatting with us about statins, member. Here are some fast facts about statins, cholesterol, and your heart health.

AGENT (2025-06-03 20:38:00+00): 1. What are statins? Statins are a type of med that helps lower your cholesterol. 
2. What is cholesterol? It’s a fatty substance in your blood that your body naturally produces. You also get cholesterol from the foods you eat. 
3. Why work on lowering your cholesterol with statins? If you have high cholesterol, you have a greater chance of heart problems — like heart attack and stroke. Statins lower your cholesterol, which minimizes those risks. 
AGENT (2025-06-03 20:39:00+00): 4. How do statins work? Statins slow down the amount of cholesterol your body makes and get rid of extra cholesterol in your blood. This keeps your heart healthy and lowers your risk of heart attack and stroke.
5. Do you still need your statin if you don’t feel high cholesterol symptoms? Yes, if your doctor has recommended it. Most people can’t feel high cholesterol. Your statin med is still hard at work lowering your cholesterol, even if you don’t feel a noticeable difference.
AGENT (2025-06-03 20:39:00+00): 6. How do you know if your statin med is working? Your doctor can regularly check your cholesterol with a blood test. Together, you can monitor your levels as you continue to take your statin.

AGENT (2025-06-03 23:39:00+00): Professional care for depression
When it comes to your mood, many different types of healthcare professionals can help. 
For example, it may be good to start with a primary care doctor. Therapists and counselors can provide talk therapy. You can do that 1:1, in a group, or with family. There are also psychiatrists who can prescribe medications.

AGENT (2025-06-03 23:40:00+00): Professional care is important because the provider has training and judgement to recommend what level of care you may need. 
For example, in some mild cases, people with depression can manage well on their own.  In more moderate and severe cases, people may need medication or more intensive therapy.

AGENT (2025-06-03 23:40:00+00): Social connection, and a feeling of belonging, are basic human needs.
Studies show that connecting with other people can reduce feelings of depression and loneliness. It doesn’t have to be in person all the time. There are many ways to feel connected.  Here are a few ideas: 
1) Call or text someone you haven’t spoken to in a while.
2) Send someone a hand written letter in the mail
3) Set up a regular family video chat or family text group.
4) Send someone a weekly photo update or a message about something you did recently. 

AGENT (2025-06-03 23:41:00+00): 5) Look into joining a ‘virtual hobby’ group to connect with others who have similar interests.  (Like an online book clubs or music groups. 
6) Look into adult education classes.
7) Look into volunteer opportunities.
8) If you are religious, consider finding connection in spiritual groups. 

AGENT (2025-06-03 23:41:00+00): Let us know if these tips are what you have in mind or if you would like to review another topic that impacts depression.

AGENT (2025-05-23 11:06:00+00): Good Morning, Tracie. Nice to hear from you. Experts have found that journaling is good for mind AND body.

 - It can improve mood, lower stress, and help people cope with challenges
- Less stress, anxiety, and depression. It can also help you cope with challenges.
- People who journal regularly have better physical functioning and more success managing chronic health problems. 

Ready to try it? Take 5 to 10 minutes to try one of these prompts —, or make up your own.

1) What are 3 to 5 things you’re grateful for today? (It can be small things like a smile from a neighbor or time with a pet, or bigger things like a promotion.)
2) What have you experienced in nature today?  Write a description of sights, sounds or smells from any time spent outdoors.
3) What are you looking forward to? Describe something you’re excited about in the upcoming week or month. 
Happy writing! We’ve sent 30 points your way.

AGENT (2025-05-28 12:15:00+00): Here are some general tips to keep in mind when buying a blood pressure monitor:

The ones that go around the upper arm are more accurate than the ones that go around the wrist. 
Automatic monitors are easier to use, because you can check your pressure by simply pushing a button.
Make sure you have the correct size. If your cuff is too small or large, your reading may be wrong.
Some monitors can sync your data with an app on your phone and help you track your blood pressure over time.
